Hello, Wisconsin!

Moved back just in time for a record cold Winter after living in the most amazing weather.

I’ve pulled away from social media & am redefining how to use this space. Not sure what all that means yet but I felt it was time to finally publicly let you all know we moved back North.

Much love to you all 💗
Thanks for still being here.

Screen time down by 64% 👏🏼

Translation: time given back to the ones that’s matter most!

Today our oldest, Paxton, is EIGHT years old! EIGHT!

Paxton is such a special little boy. He is considerate, discerning & resilient. He is strong yet soft & very determined.

I love so many things about being his mom. I still cannot believe eight years has come and gone. It wasn’t in my plans to be a mama at 23 just a few years into marriage but goodness gracious I’m so glad God holds the final say! He has blessed us beyond measure entrusting us with raising Pax!

Please help me wish him a happy bday & tell me one thing you love about him if you know him personally 💗

The last few years leave me so confused. I can sense God’s hand but the conclusions I drew up compared to my reality do not even slightly resemble one another.

I’ve felt hurt, betrayed, lost yet fulfillment, joy & hope unlike I have in any other season. My highs have been so high & my lows have been so low.

And some how every “how does this make sense, God” moment has been met with just as many “I see you so clearly” moments.

I wish I had more answers. But the reality is, I have had to let it go and live FULLY surrendered to His work. To the work he wants to do in me, in Kyle, and in everyone of my four children.

So much of me wants a redo yet I’ve grown in the valleys in ways I never did on the mountains.

You aren’t alone. But at the same time, in the alone He meets you like never before!

I’m raising a strong girl while also teaching her how to live surrendered. I’m raising a beautiful from the inside out girl. Know what your worth is & don’t settle girl.

A girl who knows how to pray. How to share truth in love girl- just so on fire for Jesus! I may not always get it right, girl, but raising you draws me closer to Jesus. Raising you requires me to be in tune with the Holy Spirit. Raising you, is an honor my girl.
Follow @momencouraged for more 💗
All the little siblings can probably relate 😂

In September my husband transitioned our family… blindly. A few weeks later I was working for storygatherings in Nashville with a baby on my hip.

Months later, we were landing in WI in full on “new season” mode. Pictures, at least for me, are more than pulling a camera out in a serious moment.

They are my reminders that when I saw nothing, God had everything under control.

He sees me. He knows me. He’s with me. And with Him, I’m whole 🖤

And that is not exclusive for me. It’s for anyone. And I’d love to walk with you on your own journey of discovering God 💗
Time is flying by. This year my goal is to get get really good at focusing on what matter most. 💗

When we moved into our home in Mississippi it was covered in gray gray gray walls. Within the first month of living there Kyle and I spent any extra time we had painting, wallpapering, redesigning and working hard to make the place more our style. We were working on a limited budget but we knew what we wanted.

Working hard ourselves & partnering with amazing companies helped us bring our dreams into fruition. We had NO clue we’d be selling the home almost to date one year after buying it.

Fast forward to the home we bought here in Wisconsin. ALL GRAY. I’m not kidding you. Even the carpet is gray. I’m going crazy guys. 😂

Nothing too profound here in this post, just a flashback shout out to incredible companies and telling my tired self that I have got to paint these walls in my home before I go too crazy.

🤪
Anyone else out there raising a little mini me that’s got a little bit of sweet and a whole lotta sass 🤟🏻🤪

8 words form Joyce Meyer that are leaving me with conviction and direction!

 Recently, @bri_brown_2 shared in a blog“I know that not everyone gets encouragement often, so I want to do my best to change that in the lives of the people I encounter.”

And that right there, is what I too want to be committed to! Whose joining me? 🤟🏻

Our entire uhaul was loaded up to leave Mississippi and make our way *back home* when our realtor called us with some very scary news.

We had already signed every paper needed, but somehow an error was made and 48 hours was needed to fix and process the mistake. Those 48 hours took 27 days.

27 days of not knowing what was happening across the country on a home that we had already left behind. 27 days of not having a home in our new town but still having to start news jobs and acclimate our kids to anew school. 27 days of living displaced but not letting our kids feels the weight of all the stress and fear that constantly flooded our mind.

As you can imagine, I learned so much in those 27 days.… and the biggest lesson I learned was truly understanding how important being grateful is. I had a hard 27 days, but i had so much to be thankful for. I could choose, which was going to get my attention? The troubles or all the good things that came from the move?

While I’m so glad to be out of the waiting period, I know God was shaping me. I needed those lessons from those hard days!

🖤pic of our new living room

The lessons you learn in the tough times really do shape you.

Keep the notes close from the dark days, look back on them and remember God doesn’t waste hardship.

A younger, more undeveloped version of myself was learning some things in 2019 that changed the trajectory of everything.

Hope has taken over some of the most hopeless places that once consumed my life. Knowing I am not able to avoid hard times, I hold the lessons close knowing that with the right perspective and next steps redemption is possible.

Praying for you tonight. If you need a little extra pray just drop an emoji- no details needed, but I’d love to cover you in prayer by name.

Every day for the last 3 years Bryn has made her way into our bed in the middle of the night. We tried correcting it, we tried offering rewards to stop it, we tried redirecting her…  but ultimately, we all felt the best when we just embraced it.

Right now, this is what feeling safe looks like for her 5 year old sleeping mind. She’s not being defiant, she is not crossing the line… yes she’s growing older but she’s still so little.

I think it’s important to draw boundaries… but I also think it’s important to remember one size does not fit all. God gave you wisdom and discernment as a parent to know what the best decision for your family is.

🤍

Looks like we made it. We knew we’d get here some day.

If you’ve been here since 2018 - then you’d know that it has been quite the ride for us. We may have taken the long road and have had to learn some painful lessons the hard way, but I can honestly say those seasons have taught me what I know today and strengthened me in ways that Im not sure a mountain top ever could.
 
Looks like we are making it. Look how far we have come, Kyle 🖤

One year ago I made the post *scroll to see* completely blinded to the reality that six months later we’d sell that home in the south and purchase a different one 900 miles back up north.

I meant every word when I said we saw how it was *the best choice* but it’s kind of bazaar a year later to be able to say coming back was *the best choice*

I guess I’m learning that best doesn’t always mean forever. It can be for right now. 18 months ago when we moved to MS that was the right choice and closing that door when we did, also the right choice.

God gives. God takes away. Our choices in between lead us to our realities. But in the mean time I’m soaking up, capturing, and living in the moment because I haven’t figured out how to slow time down and no matter where we go or where we end up, the six of us being healthy, connected & making memories that last a life time is at the top of my priority list.

And you know what? That year in Mississippi was DANG good. And showcasing this on my table is something I’m proud of, not ashamed of. I’d move anywhere and everywhere with my crew all over again! But I’m also real excited to be staying put.

Want to make the most of your trip to six flags? #ad Here are a few of our family’s tips after quite a few trips to the park:

1. Have the group members who are not riding wait at the exit right before you are about to get on the ride. This is teaching our kids the importance of mom and dad having fun too and as you see, the kiddos love cheering on mom and dad after their ride! If not all people are riding the same ride, text which seat you are on so everyone can wave and enjoy the ride with you.

2. Come with a YES mentality! People don’t want to ride the same rides? Yes to both. We tell everyone in our group to think about 2 rides they absolutely need to ride and we do our best to make sure everyone gets to do their top two! Everyone wants ice cream? Yes! We even let our son play an arcade game and guess what? HE WON!

3. Good walking shoes really do matter for the kids and the adults! You will be on your feet A LOT, wear what is comfortable for YOU!

4. Get a babysitter and do all the rides with just your spouse and friends. We did that this past week and we DID not regret it!

5. Download the app and take a look at the schedule for the day. Enjoy the shows, try the new food items, experience the different activities and make it A DAY TO REMEMBER!

Six Flags has something for everyone. You will not regret spending the day here at the park. #SixFlagsGreatAmerica

Horatio Spafford wrote this hymn as a response to life altering news. He had just sent his wife & 4 daughters on a ship for family vacation planning to join them after they settled. The ship was involved in a terrible accident resulting in the death of those 5 women. 

In response to this devastating news, Spafford writes:

When peace like a river, attendeth my way
When sorrows like sea billows roll
Whatever my lot, thou hast taught me to say
It is well, it is well, with my soul
It is well
With my soul
It is well, it is well with my soul
Though Satan should buffet, though trials should come
Let this blest assurance control
That Christ has regarded my helpless estate
And hath shed His own blood for my soul
It is well (it is well)
With my soul (with my soul)
It is well, it is well with my soul
My sin, oh, the bliss of this glorious thought!
My sin, not in part but the whole
Is nailed to the cross, and I bear it no more
Praise the Lord, praise the Lord, o my soul!
It is well (it is well)
With my soul (with my soul)
It is well, it is well with my soul
It is well (it is well)
With my soul (with my soul)
It is well, it is well with my soul.

We are responsible for the environments we allow our kiddos to be in. We get to be the gate keeper on relationships that don’t measure up and cause them to question their worth.

It is up to us as parents to give them the tools they need to overcome the hard things they’ll endure in this lifetime.

We are in charge of creating the memories they’ll love looking back on one day. This is it for them. This is their ONE and ONLY childhood, let’s just let them be kids 💕

Do yourself a favor and grab some Kleenex and make this one of your kiddos 😭 Or maybe don’t because I can’t stop crying now.

Lately when I’ve been looking at Bryn Ive seen a whole new version of her. This one is a little more calculated and thought out. She can read and ask big questions. Instead of needing help, she’s offering it. She doesn’t cry when trying new things anymore.

She doesn’t need me like she used to, it’s different. I love this different but I miss my toddler Bryn too. As she blossoms and grows and becomes a little more of who Gods called her to be, I’m hopeful she will always know how proud of her we are for just being Bryn 🫶🏻

Knowing the end goal always helps 💕

What kind of things do you want your kiddos to say about their childhood? These days are their future memories. They’ll either want to model their parenting after this or know what they don’t want.

Intentional parenting doesn’t mean they can’t have the freedom to just be the little kids they are meant to be. It just means that you are the adult are taking time to know the path you are on as a family.

What things are you saying yes to that you need to start saying no to? What people need a boundary? What projects need to go on hold? What projects need to be started?

You got this mama! Rooting for you!

Happy Birthday Kyle ✨

Our kids are learning what it means to be patient, kind, and family focused from the example you set just by being who you are. I see much of you in our kids & I’m thankful for that! 💕

Exhale. When you are in a spot like this, it forces you to find strength and vulnerability in sacred places. I believe I need moms who have gone before me to lead me and teach me and I have found advice and mentorship in some wonderful people. But at the end of the day, it’ll never replace the gap that my inner child still calls for.

My mother in law passed away 5 years ago when I was just 2.5 years into my motherhood journey. And about 2 years ago, for the sake of my own mental health and healing journey my relationship with my own mother required me to take a step back and that was met with anger and resistance.

I am doing better than fine. I am healing. I am figuring this motherhood thing out. I’m thankful for the ladies in my life who CHOSE to step in when others stepped out. 

I have hidden this part of my story out of respect for others & quite honestly my own embarrassment but I am learning to be proud of who I am and what I have overcome from putting my trust in Jesus, letting my walls down with the right people & growing along side my husband to provide a healthy home for our family ✨
